BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:w6p4pRXH6p3uEM7rykS7-
SUMMARY:Smarty Pints! Plants\, Pollinators\, and Cannabis Chemistry
DTSTAMP:20260413T005337Z
DTSTART:20260421T013000Z
DESCRIPTION:Spring has sprung\, so we’re bringing you pollinators and weed\
	\(s\\) for Smarty Pints this month! On April 20 we’re back with more timel
	y talks\, on how changing snow conditions affect plants and their pollinat
	ors and on the chemistry of cannabis\, beer\, and essential oils. See you 
	at 6:30 in the taproom!\n\n🐝Prof. Berry Brosi\n\nProfessor\, UW Biology\n\
	nExecutive Director\, MeadoWatch\n\nClimate-driven plant-pollinator timing
	 mismatches: does biodiversity provide backup?\n\nPollination is essential
	 for plant reproduction\, biodiversity\, and agriculture. Scientists are i
	ncreasingly worried about timing mismatches between plants and their polli
	nators\, driven by climate change. Plants and insects use different enviro
	nmental cues \\(temperature\, day length\, snowmelt\\) to time when they b
	loom and when they become active\, and climate change is increasingly caus
	ing these cues to fall out of sync.\n\nMost research on this problem has f
	ocused on individual plants in isolation\, which tend to show negative eff
	ects from mistimed pollination. But in nature\, most plants are visited by
	 multiple pollinator species and vice versa—so could that biodiversity act
	 as a buffer against these mismatches?\n\nTo find out\, we conducted a stu
	dy in the Colorado Rockies\, where snowmelt largely controls when plants b
	loom. We experimentally manipulated snowmelt in large plots containing mul
	tiple plant species and many individuals of each. Come to the talk to find
	 out what we discovered about how pollinators responded—and whether the pl
	ant pollination suffered!\n\n🧪 Jim Roe\n\nAnalytical Chemist\, SoRSE Techn
	ology\n\nVolatile compounds in cannabis\, essential oils\, and beer\n\nWha
	t’s the chemistry behind your favorite smokes\, scents\, and suds? We’ll d
	iscuss terpenes and other -enes\, -ones\, and -ols that you definitely did
	 not forget after that o-chem final back in college. Jim Roe has made a ca
	reer out of chemistry instrumentation and analysis\, from a research scien
	tist managing the UW Chemistry department’s instrument lab to a field serv
	ice engineer for equipment spanning the alphabet \\(GCMS\, HPLC\, FTIR… ho
	ller for your favorite\\). He has consulted on setting up cannabis laborat
	ories around the Pacific Northwest\, and currently works in research and d
	evelopment for water-soluble emulsions of cannabinoids\, terpenes\, hop oi
	ls\, and other compounds used in food\, beverages\, and topicals.\n\nhttps
	://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/smarty-pints-plants-pollinators-a
	nd-cannabis-chemistry/18476514/2026-04-20T00
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/smarty-pints-plants-polli
	nators-and-cannabis-chemistry/18476514/2026-04-20T00
LOCATION:Burke-Gilman Brewing Company\, 3626 NE 45th St\, Suite 102\, Seatt
	le\, WA
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
